Japan as the front-runner of super-aged societies: Perspectives from medicine 
and medical care in Japan.

Arai H(1), Ouchi Y(2), Toba K(3), Endo T(4), Shimokado K(5), Tsubota K(6), 
Matsuo S(7), Mori H(8), Yumura W(9), Yokode M(1), Rakugi H(10), Ohshima S(3).

Author information:
(1)Kyoto University Graduate School of Medicine, Kyoto, Japan.
(2)Toranomon Hospital, Tokyo, Japan.
(3)National Center for Geriatrics and Gerontology, Obu, Japan.
(4)Tokyo Metropolitan Institute of Gerontology, Tokyo, Japan.
(5)Tokyo Medical and Dental University Graduate School, Tokyo, Japan.
(6)Keio University School of Medicine, Tokyo, Japan.
(7)Nagoya University Graduate School of Medicine, Nagoya, Japan.
(8)Tokai University, Isehara, Japan.
(9)International University of Health and Welfare Hospital, Tochigi, Japan.
(10)Osaka University Graduate School of Medicine, Osaka, Japan.

BACKGROUND: The demographic structure of a country changes dramatically with 
increasing trends toward general population aging and declining birth rates. In 
Japan, the percentage of the elderly population (aged ≥65 years) reached 25% in 
2013; it is expected to exceed 30% in 2025 and reach 39.9% in 2060. The national 
total population has been decreasing steadily since its peak reached in 2008, 
and it is expected to fall to the order of 80 million in 2060. Of the total 
population, those aged ≥75 years accounted for 12.3% as of 2013, and this is 
expected to reach 26.9% in 2060. As the demographic structure changes, the 
disease structure changes, and therefore the medical care demand changes. To 
accommodate the medical care demand changes, it is necessary to secure a system 
for providing medical care. Japan has thus far attained remarkable achievements 
in medical care, seeking a better prognosis for survival; however, its medical 
care demand is anticipated to change both qualitatively and quantitatively. As 
diseases in the elderly, particularly in the old-old population, are often 
intractable, conventional medical care must be upgraded to one suitable for an 
aged society. What is required to this end is a shift from "cure-seeking medical 
care" focusing on disease treatment on an organ-specific basis to "cure and 
support-seeking medical care" with treatments reprioritized to maximize the 
